# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acclimatisation-society
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] The Otago Acclimatisation Society was operating by 1864.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] By 1869, it was receiving £500 per year from the Otago provincial government to bring in familiar British species, notably small birds, such as starlings, blackbirds, sparrows, chaffinches, of which populations thrive throughout the country today.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] In 1867 the first of a series of Animal Protection Acts was passed to provide protection to many of the introduced animals and formally recognised the Acclimation Societies in New Zealand.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] Later that year the importation of trout and salmon was enabled by the passing of the Trout and Salmon Act.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] Hawke's Bay Acclimatisation Society was formed in 1868, with land purchaser and politician, Donald McLean, as its first president.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] Wellington's Acclimatisation Society got under way in May 1871 with 62 members.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] President A.Ludlam, vice presidents: Archdeacon Stock, Dr Hector, J.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] Their first committee was: Hunter, Pearce, Krull, Laing, Bannatyne, Denton, Travers, G.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] In October 1884 it was reconstituted under the Animals Protection Act 1880 having extended its membership and reconstituted itself as the Wellington and Wairarapa District Acclimatisation Society.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] The Society's income from shooting licences was much greater than from fishing licences, 16,700 fish had been liberated in the past year and if that continued the area's fishing might soon be the equal of anywhere else in New Zealand.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] It was also noted that unless settlers became more ready to prevent poaching birds would disappear very rapidly.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] The Canterbury acclimatisation society was known for some more unusual introductions including the African Lion.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] Not only did they import animals, but they also exported them.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] They received some financial assistance from government, for example £150 from the provincial government of Canterbury in 1867 and £300 from the national government in 1905.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] To "speak to the government with a united voice on any special subject" a formal association of acclimatisation societies was approved at their annual conference in Wellington in the summer of 1903 and given the name New Zealand Acclimatisation Society.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-societies-in-new-zealand] In 1990 they became regional fish and game councils – together, Fish and Game New Zealand.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] It is now widely understood that introducing species to foreign environments is often harmful to native species and to their ecosystems.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] For example, in Australia the environment was seriously harmed by overgrazing by rabbits.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] In North America house sparrows displaced and killed native birds.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] In New Zealand, introduced mammals such as possums and cats became threats to indigenous plants, birds and lizards.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Around the world, salamander populations are threatened by introduced fungal infections.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Consequently, the deliberate introduction of new species is now illegal in some countries.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Alfred Russel Wallace attempted to define acclimatisation in his contribution on the subject in the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, 11th edition (1911).
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Wallace tried to differentiate the concept from other terms, such as "domestication" and "naturalisation".
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] He noted that a domesticated animal could live in environments controlled by humans.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Naturalisation, he suggested, included the process of acclimatisation, which involved "gradual adjustment".
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] The idea, at least in France, was associated with Lamarckism, and Wallace noted that some, such as Charles Darwin, denied the possibility of forcing individual animals to adjust.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] However, Wallace pointed out that there was the possibility that there were variations among individuals and so some could have the ability to adapt to new environments.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] The first acclimatisation society was *La Societé Zoologique d'Acclimatation*, founded in Paris by Isidore Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire, on 10 May 1854.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] It was essentially an offshoot of the National Museum of Natural History in Paris, and the other staff included Jean Louis Armand de Quatrefages, Antoine César Becquerel and his son Alexandre.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Saint-Hilaire subscribed to the Lamarckian idea that humans and animals could be forced to adapt to new environments.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] The French society established a branch in Algeria, as well as the *Jardin d'Acclimatation* in Paris in 1861, to showcase not just new animals and plants but also people from other lands.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Rewards in the form of medals were offered for anyone in the colonies who established breeding animals.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] The rules were that at least six specimens had to be maintained, with at least two instances of breeding in captivity.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] After Saint-Hilaire's death in 1861, the Society was headed by Édouard Drouyn de Lhuys, foreign minister to Napoleon III, and many of the functionaries were diplomats who established ties with officers in the colonies both French and foreign.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Franco-British as well as Franco-Australian ties were involved in the movements of plants and animals.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Australian acacias, for instance, were introduced in Algeria by the French, and by the British in South Africa.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] François Laporte, naturalist and consul in Melbourne, and Ferdinand von Mueller of the Acclimatisation Society of Victoria, were involved in the transfer of many plant species out of Australia.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] In some cases, those movements were not direct but via Paris and Kew.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] The British acclimatisation society originated from an idea proposed by the management of *The Field* magazine.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] A meeting was held on 21 January 1859, at the London Tavern on Bishopsgate Street.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] The attendees included Richard Owen at the head of the table, and the servings included a large pike, American partridges, a young bean goose and an African eland.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] At the meeting, Mitchell and others suggested that many of those exotic animals could live in the British wilderness.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] A few days later, Owen wrote to *The Times*, praising the taste of the eland and advocating animal introductions.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] On 26 June 1860, another meeting was held and the Acclimatisation Society was formally founded in London.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] A year later, the Secretary to the Society, Frank Buckland, a popular naturalist known for his taste in exotic meats, noted the "success" of the Society in introducing peafowl, common pheasant, European swans, starlings and linnets into Australia, through the efforts of Edward Wilson.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] One of the supporters of the Society was Burdett Coutts.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Other such societies spread quickly around the world, particularly to European colonies in the Americas, Australia and New Zealand.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] In many instances they existed both as societies for the study of natural history as well as to improve the success rate of introduced species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] In 1850, English sparrows were introduced into America, and Eugene Schieffelin introduced starlings in 1890.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] The appeal of acclimatisation societies in the British settler colonies, particularly Australia and New Zealand, was the belief that the addition of European species would improve the natural environments.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] There was also an element of nostalgia in the desire of European colonists to see familiar species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] At the time, the acclimatisation societies did not see themselves as opposed to the conservation of native species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] In fact, acclimitisation societies often advocated for protection of native game, just as conservation groups likewise supported protections for many introduced species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] The Acclimatisation Society of Victoria was established in 1861.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Speaking to the Society, George Bennett pointed out how it was important to have such an organisation, citing the example of the Earl of Knowsley, who had been conducting successful experiments in private, the results of which had been lost with his death.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] A major proponent of importing and exporting trees and plants was Ferdinand von Mueller.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Introductions of commercially valuable species or game species were also made.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] In some instances, the results were disastrous, such as the economic and ecological disaster of introducing rabbits to Australia or possums to New Zealand.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] The dire effects were rapidly felt and a Rabbit Nuisance Act was passed in New Zealand in 1876.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] To make matters worse, there was a suggestion that weasels and stoats should be imported to control the rabbits.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Palmer of California wrote about the dangers of animal introduction.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] In 1906, the editors of the Avicultural Magazine were decidedly against the idea of bird introductions.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] The emergence of the field of ecology transformed expert and public opinion on introductions and gave way to new rules.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Quarantine regulations began to be set up instead.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Beginning in New Zealand, some of the acclimatisation societies transformed themselves into fish and game organisations.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Introduction of the Nile hippopotamus to the United States on a massive scale was proposed by Louisiana Representative Robert F.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] The purpose was supposed to increase the American production and accessibility of meat, as well as to combat the spread of another previously introduced invasive species, the water hyacinth.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] The hippos were supposed to feast on water hyacinth and then be slaughtered for meat by ranchers.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Broussard did not mention or wasn't aware of how dangerous Nile hippos are, as they kill around 500 people a year.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Additionally, water hyacinth isn't seen as an attractive meal by herbivores, having a body composed in 95% of water and very little nutrition.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Other animals were also suggested for introduction, such as rhinoceroses or antelopes.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatisation-society] Others who supported the introduction of hippopotamuses were Fritz Duquesne and William Newton Irwin.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] The nouns *acclimatization* and *acclimation* (and the corresponding verbs *acclimatize* and *acclimate*) are widely regarded as synonymous, both in general vocabulary and in medical vocabulary.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] The synonym *acclimation* is less commonly encountered, and fewer dictionaries enter it.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] In order to maintain performance across a range of environmental conditions, there are several strategies organisms use to acclimate.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] In response to changes in temperature, organisms can change the biochemistry of cell membranes making them more fluid in cold temperatures and less fluid in warm temperatures by increasing the number of membrane proteins.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] In response to certain stressors, some organisms express so-called heat shock proteins that act as molecular chaperones and reduce denaturation by guiding the folding and refolding of proteins.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] It has been shown that organisms which are acclimated to high or low temperatures display relatively high resting levels of heat shock proteins so that when they are exposed to even more extreme temperatures the proteins are readily available.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Expression of heat shock proteins and regulation of membrane fluidity are just two of many biochemical methods organisms use to acclimate to novel environments.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Organisms are able to change several characteristics relating to their morphology in order to maintain performance in novel environments.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] For example, birds often increase their organ size to increase their metabolism.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] This can take the form of an increase in the mass of nutritional organs or heat-producing organs, like the pectorals (with the latter being more consistent across species).
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] While the capacity for acclimatization has been documented in thousands of species, researchers still know very little about how and why organisms acclimate in the way that they do.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Since researchers first began to study acclimation, the overwhelming hypothesis has been that all acclimation serves to enhance the performance of the organism.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] This idea has come to be known as the beneficial acclimation hypothesis.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Despite such widespread support for the beneficial acclimation hypothesis, not all studies show that acclimation always serves to enhance performance (*See beneficial acclimation hypothesis*).
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] One of the major objections to the beneficial acclimation hypothesis is that it assumes that there are no costs associated with acclimation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] However, there are likely to be costs associated with acclimation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] These include the cost of sensing the environmental conditions and regulating responses, producing structures required for plasticity (such as the energetic costs in expressing heat shock proteins), and genetic costs (such as linkage of plasticity-related genes with harmful genes).
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Given the shortcomings of the beneficial acclimation hypothesis, researchers are continuing to search for a theory that will be supported by empirical data.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] The degree to which organisms are able to acclimate is dictated by their phenotypic plasticity or the ability of an organism to change certain traits.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Recent research in the study of acclimation capacity has focused more heavily on the evolution of phenotypic plasticity rather than acclimation responses.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Scientists believe that when they understand more about how organisms evolved the capacity to acclimate, they will better understand acclimation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Many plants, such as maple trees, irises, and tomatoes, can survive freezing temperatures if the temperature gradually drops lower and lower each night over a period of days or weeks.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] The same drop might kill them if it occurred suddenly.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Studies have shown that tomato plants that were acclimated to higher temperature over several days were more efficient at photosynthesis at relatively high temperatures than were plants that were not allowed to acclimate.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] In the orchid *Phalaenopsis*, phenylpropanoid enzymes are enhanced in the process of plant acclimatisation at different levels of photosynthetic photon flux.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Sheep grow very thick wool in cold, damp climates.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Fish are able to adjust only gradually to changes in water temperature and quality.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Tropical fish sold at pet stores are often kept in acclimatization bags until this process is complete.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Lowe & Vance (1995) were able to show that lizards acclimated to warm temperatures could maintain a higher running speed at warmer temperatures than lizards that were not acclimated to warm conditions.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Fruit flies that develop at relatively cooler or warmer temperatures have increased cold or heat tolerance as adults, respectively (*See* Developmental plasticity).
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] The salt content of sweat and urine decreases as people acclimatize to hot conditions.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Plasma volume, heart rate, and capillary activation are also affected.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Acclimatization to high altitude continues for months or even years after initial ascent, and ultimately enables humans to survive in an environment that, without acclimatization, would kill them.
[src:acclimatisation-society/acclimatise] Humans who migrate permanently to a higher altitude naturally acclimatize to their new environment by developing an increase in the number of red blood cells to increase the oxygen carrying capacity of the blood, in order to compensate for lower levels of oxygen intake.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] In biology, **adaptation** has three related meanings.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Firstly, it is the dynamic evolutionary process of natural selection that fits organisms to their environment, enhancing their evolutionary fitness.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Secondly, it is a state reached by the population during that process.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Thirdly, it is a phenotypic trait or **adaptive trait**, with a functional role in each individual organism, that is maintained and has evolved through natural selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Historically, adaptation has been described from the time of the ancient Greek philosophers such as Empedocles and Aristotle.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] In 18th and 19th-century natural theology, adaptation was taken as evidence for the existence of a deity.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Charles Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace proposed instead that it was explained by natural selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Adaptation is related to biological fitness, which governs the rate of evolution as measured by changes in allele frequencies.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Often, two or more species co-adapt and co-evolve as they develop adaptations that interlock with those of the other species, such as with flowering plants and pollinating insects.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] In mimicry, species evolve to resemble other species; in mimicry this is a mutually beneficial co-evolution as each of a group of strongly defended species (such as wasps able to sting) come to advertise their defences in the same way.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Features evolved for one purpose may be co-opted for a different one, as when the insulating feathers of dinosaurs were co-opted for bird flight.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Adaptation is a major topic in the philosophy of biology, as it concerns function and purpose (teleology).
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Some biologists try to avoid terms which imply purpose in adaptation, not least because they suggest a deity's intentions, but others note that adaptation is necessarily purposeful.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Adaptation is an observable fact of life accepted by philosophers and natural historians from ancient times, independently of their views on evolution, but their explanations differed.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Empedocles did not believe that adaptation required a final cause (a purpose), but thought that it "came about naturally, since such things survived." Aristotle did believe in final causes, but assumed that species were fixed.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] In natural theology, adaptation was interpreted as the work of a deity and as evidence for the existence of God.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] William Paley believed that organisms were perfectly adapted to the lives they led, an argument that shadowed Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, who had argued that God had brought about "the best of all possible worlds." Voltaire's satire Dr.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Pangloss is a parody of this optimistic idea, and David Hume also argued against design.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Charles Darwin broke with the tradition by emphasising the flaws and limitations which occurred in the animal and plant worlds.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Jean-Baptiste Lamarck proposed a tendency for organisms to become more complex, moving up a ladder of progress, plus "the influence of circumstances", usually expressed as *use and disuse*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] This second, subsidiary element of his theory is what is now called Lamarckism, a proto-evolutionary hypothesis of the inheritance of acquired characteristics, intended to explain adaptations by natural means.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Other natural historians, such as Buffon, accepted adaptation, and some also accepted evolution, without voicing their opinions as to the mechanism.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] This illustrates the real merit of Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace, and secondary figures such as Henry Walter Bates, for putting forward a mechanism whose significance had only been glimpsed previously.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] A century later, experimental field studies and breeding experiments by people such as E.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Ford and Theodosius Dobzhansky produced evidence that natural selection was not only the 'engine' behind adaptation, but was a much stronger force than had previously been thought.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Adaptation is primarily a process rather than a physical form or part of a body.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] An internal parasite (such as a liver fluke) can illustrate the distinction: such a parasite may have a very simple bodily structure, but nevertheless the organism is highly adapted to its specific environment.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] From this we see that adaptation is not just a matter of visible traits: in such parasites critical adaptations take place in the life cycle, which is often quite complex.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] However, as a practical term, "adaptation" often refers to a *product*: those features of a species which result from the process.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Many aspects of an animal or plant can be correctly called adaptations, though there are always some features whose function remains in doubt.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] By using the term *adaptation* for the evolutionary *process*, and *adaptive trait* for the bodily part or function (the product), one may distinguish the two different senses of the word.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Adaptation is one of the two main processes that explain the observed diversity of species, such as the different species of Darwin's finches.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The other process is speciation, in which new species arise, typically through reproductive isolation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] An example widely used today to study the interplay of adaptation and speciation is the evolution of cichlid fish in African lakes, where the question of reproductive isolation is complex.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Adaptation is not always a simple matter where the ideal phenotype evolves for a given environment.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] An organism must be viable at all stages of its development and at all stages of its evolution.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] This places *constraints* on the evolution of development, behaviour, and structure of organisms.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The main constraint, over which there has been much debate, is the requirement that each genetic and phenotypic change during evolution should be relatively small, because developmental systems are so complex and interlinked.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] However, it is not clear what "relatively small" should mean, for example polyploidy in plants is a reasonably common large genetic change.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The origin of eukaryotic endosymbiosis is a more dramatic example.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] All adaptations help organisms survive in their ecological niches.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The adaptive traits may be structural, behavioural or physiological.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Structural adaptations are physical features of an organism, such as shape, body covering, armament, and internal organization.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Behavioural adaptations are inherited systems of behaviour, whether inherited in detail as instincts, or as a neuropsychological capacity for learning.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Examples include searching for food, mating, and vocalizations.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Physiological adaptations permit the organism to perform special functions such as making venom, secreting slime, and phototropism, but also involve more general functions such as growth and development, temperature regulation, ionic balance and other aspects of homeostasis.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Adaptation affects all aspects of the life of an organism.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] is the state of being adapted: the degree to which an organism is able to live and reproduce in a given set of habitats.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] is an aspect of the developmental pattern of the organism which enables or enhances the probability of that organism surviving and reproducing.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Adaptation differs from flexibility, acclimatization, and learning, all of which are changes during life which are not inherited.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Flexibility deals with the relative capacity of an organism to maintain itself in different habitats: its degree of specialization.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Acclimatization describes automatic physiological adjustments during life; learning means alteration in behavioural performance during life.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Flexibility stems from phenotypic plasticity, the ability of an organism with a given genotype (genetic type) to change its phenotype (observable characteristics) in response to changes in its habitat, or to move to a different habitat.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The degree of flexibility is inherited, and varies between individuals.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] A highly specialized animal or plant lives only in a well-defined habitat, eats a specific type of food, and cannot survive if its needs are not met.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Many herbivores are like this; extreme examples are koalas which depend on *Eucalyptus*, and giant pandas which require bamboo.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] A generalist, on the other hand, eats a range of food, and can survive in many different conditions.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Examples are humans, rats, crabs and many carnivores.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The *tendency* to behave in a specialized or exploratory manner is inherited—it is an adaptation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Rather different is developmental flexibility: "An animal or plant is developmentally flexible if when it is raised in or transferred to new conditions, it changes in structure so that it is better fitted to survive in the new environment," writes the evolutionary biologist John Maynard Smith.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] If humans move to a higher altitude, respiration and physical exertion become a problem, but after spending time in high altitude conditions they acclimatize to the reduced partial pressure of oxygen, such as by producing more red blood cells.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The ability to acclimatize is an adaptation, but the acclimatization itself is not.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The reproductive rate declines, but deaths from some tropical diseases also go down.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Over a longer period of time, some people are better able to reproduce at high altitudes than others.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] They contribute more heavily to later generations, and gradually by natural selection the whole population becomes adapted to the new conditions.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] This has demonstrably occurred, as the observed performance of long-term communities at higher altitude is significantly better than the performance of new arrivals, even when the new arrivals have had time to acclimatize.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] There is a relationship between adaptedness and the concept of fitness used in population genetics.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Differences in fitness between genotypes predict the rate of evolution by natural selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Natural selection changes the relative frequencies of alternative phenotypes, insofar as they are heritable.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] However, a phenotype with high adaptedness may not have high fitness.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Dobzhansky mentioned the example of the Californian redwood, which is highly adapted, but a relict species in danger of extinction.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Elliott Sober commented that adaptation was a retrospective concept since it implied something about the history of a trait, whereas fitness predicts a trait's future.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The absolute contribution to the next generation by a genotype or a class of genotypes.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] when applied to the population as a whole.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The extent to which a phenotype fits its local ecological niche.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Sewall Wright proposed that populations occupy *adaptive peaks* on a fitness landscape.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] To evolve to another, higher peak, a population would first have to pass through a valley of maladaptive intermediate stages, and might be "trapped" on a peak that is not optimally adapted.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Before Darwin, adaptation was seen as a fixed relationship between an organism and its habitat.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] It was not appreciated that as the climate changed, so did the habitat; and as the habitat changed, so did the biota.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Also, habitats are subject to changes in their biota: for example, invasions of species from other areas.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The relative numbers of species in a given habitat are always changing.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Change is the rule, though much depends on the speed and degree of the change.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] When the habitat changes, three main things may happen to a resident population: habitat tracking, genetic change or extinction.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] In fact, all three things may occur in sequence.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Of these three effects only genetic change brings about adaptation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] When a habitat changes, the resident population typically moves to more suitable places; this is the typical response of flying insects or oceanic organisms, which have wide (though not unlimited) opportunity for movement.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] This common response is called *habitat tracking*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] It is one explanation put forward for the periods of apparent stasis in the fossil record (the punctuated equilibrium theory).
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Without mutation, the ultimate source of all genetic variation, there would be no genetic changes and no subsequent adaptation through evolution by natural selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Genetic change occurs in a population when mutation increases or decreases in its initial frequency followed by random genetic drift, migration, recombination or natural selection act on this genetic variation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] One example is that the first pathways of enzyme-based metabolism at the very origin of life on Earth may have been co-opted components of the already-existing purine nucleotide metabolism, a metabolic pathway that evolved in an ancient RNA world.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The co-option requires new mutations and through natural selection, the population then adapts genetically to its present circumstances.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Genetic changes may result in entirely new or gradual change to visible structures, or they may adjust physiological activity in a way that suits the habitat.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The varying shapes of the beaks of Darwin's finches, for example, are driven by adaptive mutations in the ALX1 gene.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The coat color of different wild mouse species matches their environments, whether black lava or light sand, owing to adaptive mutations in the melanocortin 1 receptor and other melanin pathway genes.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Physiological resistance to the heart poisons (cardiac glycosides) that monarch butterflies store in their bodies to protect themselves from predators are driven by adaptive mutations in the target of the poison, the sodium pump, resulting in target site insensitivity.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] These same adaptive mutations and similar changes at the same amino acid sites were found to evolve in a parallel manner in distantly related insects that feed on the same plants, and even in a bird that feeds on monarchs through convergent evolution, a hallmark of adaptation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Convergence at the gene-level across distantly related species can arise because of evolutionary constraint.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Habitats and biota do frequently change over time and space.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Therefore, it follows that the process of adaptation is never fully complete.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Over time, it may happen that the environment changes little, and the species comes to fit its surroundings better and better, resulting in stabilizing selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] On the other hand, it may happen that changes in the environment occur suddenly, and then the species becomes less and less well adapted.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The only way for it to climb back up that fitness peak is via the introduction of new genetic variation for natural selection to act upon.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Seen like this, adaptation is a genetic *tracking process*, which goes on all the time to some extent, but especially when the population cannot or does not move to another, less hostile area.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Given enough genetic change, as well as specific demographic conditions, an adaptation may be enough to bring a population back from the brink of extinction in a process called evolutionary rescue.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Adaptation does affect, to some extent, every species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Leigh Van Valen thought that even in a stable environment, because of antagonistic species interactions and limited resources, a species must constantly had to adapt to maintain its relative standing.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] This became known as the Red Queen hypothesis, as seen in host-parasite interactions.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Existing genetic variation and mutation were the traditional sources of material on which natural selection could act.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] In addition, horizontal gene transfer is possible between organisms in different species, using mechanisms as varied as gene cassettes, plasmids, transposons and viruses such as bacteriophages.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] In coevolution, where the existence of one species is tightly bound up with the life of another species, new or 'improved' adaptations which occur in one species are often followed by the appearance and spread of corresponding features in the other species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] In other words, each species triggers reciprocal natural selection in the other.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] These co-adaptational relationships are intrinsically dynamic, and may continue on a trajectory for millions of years, as has occurred in the relationship between flowering plants and pollinating insects.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Bates' work on Amazonian butterflies led him to develop the first scientific account of mimicry, especially the kind of mimicry which bears his name: Batesian mimicry.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] This is the mimicry by a palatable species of an unpalatable or noxious species (the model), gaining a selective advantage as predators avoid the model and therefore also the mimic.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Mimicry is thus an anti-predator adaptation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] A common example seen in temperate gardens is the hoverfly (Syrphidae), many of which—though bearing no sting—mimic the warning coloration of aculeate Hymenoptera (wasps and bees).
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Such mimicry does not need to be perfect to improve the survival of the palatable species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Bates, Wallace and Fritz Müller believed that Batesian and Müllerian mimicry provided evidence for the action of natural selection, a view which is now standard amongst biologists.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] All adaptations have a downside: horse legs are great for running on grass, but they cannot scratch their backs; mammals' hair helps temperature, but offers a niche for ectoparasites; the only flying penguins do is under water.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Adaptations serving different functions may be mutually destructive.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Compromise and makeshift occur widely, not perfection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Selection pressures pull in different directions, and the adaptation that results is some kind of compromise.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Consider the antlers of the Irish elk, (often supposed to be far too large; in deer antler size has an allometric relationship to body size).
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Antlers serve positively for defence against predators, and to score victories in the annual rut.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] But they are costly in terms of resources.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Their size during the last glacial period presumably depended on the relative gain and loss of reproductive capacity in the population of elks during that time.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] As another example, camouflage to avoid detection is destroyed when vivid coloration is displayed at mating time.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Here the risk to life is counterbalanced by the necessity for reproduction.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Stream-dwelling salamanders, such as Caucasian salamander or Gold-striped salamander have very slender, long bodies, perfectly adapted to life at the banks of fast small rivers and mountain brooks.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Elongated body protects their larvae from being washed out by current.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] However, elongated body increases risk of desiccation and decreases dispersal ability of the salamanders; it also negatively affects their fecundity.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] As a result, fire salamander, less perfectly adapted to the mountain brook habitats, is in general more successful, have a higher fecundity and broader geographic range.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The peacock's ornamental train (grown anew in time for each mating season) is a famous adaptation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] It must reduce his maneuverability and flight, and is hugely conspicuous; also, its growth costs food resources.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The recognition of sexual selection was for a long time in abeyance, but has been rehabilitated.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The conflict between the size of the human foetal brain at birth, (which cannot be larger than about 400 cm3, else it will not get through the mother's pelvis) and the size needed for an adult brain (about 1400 cm3), means the brain of a newborn child is quite immature.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The most vital things in human life (locomotion, speech) just have to wait while the brain grows and matures.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] That is the result of the birth compromise.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Much of the problem comes from our upright bipedal stance, without which our pelvis could be shaped more suitably for birth.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] As another example, the long neck of a giraffe brings benefits but at a cost.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The neck of a giraffe can be up to 2 m (6 ft 7 in) in length.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The benefits are that it can be used for inter-species competition or for foraging on tall trees where shorter herbivores cannot reach.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The cost is that a long neck is heavy and adds to the animal's body mass, requiring additional energy to build the neck and to carry its weight around.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Pre-adaptation occurs when a population has characteristics which by chance are suited for a set of conditions not previously experienced.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] For example, the polyploid cordgrass *Spartina townsendii* is better adapted than either of its parent species to their own habitat of saline marsh and mud-flats.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Among domestic animals, the White Leghorn chicken is markedly more resistant to vitamin B1 deficiency than other breeds; on a plentiful diet this makes no difference, but on a restricted diet this preadaptation could be decisive.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Pre-adaptation may arise because a natural population carries a huge quantity of genetic variability.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] In diploid eukaryotes, this is a consequence of the system of sexual reproduction, where mutant alleles get partially shielded, for example, by genetic dominance.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Microorganisms, with their huge populations, also carry a great deal of genetic variability.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The word is controversial because it is teleological and the entire concept of natural selection depends on the presence of genetic variation, regardless of the population size of a species in question.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Features that now appear as adaptations sometimes arose by co-option of existing traits, evolved for some other purpose.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The classic example is the ear ossicles of mammals, which we know from paleontological and embryological evidence originated in the upper and lower jaws and the hyoid bone of their synapsid ancestors, and further back still were part of the gill arches of early fish.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The word *exaptation* was coined to cover these common evolutionary shifts in function.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The flight feathers of birds evolved from the much earlier feathers of dinosaurs, which might have been used for insulation or for display.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Animals including earthworms, beavers and humans use some of their adaptations to modify their surroundings, so as to maximize their chances of surviving and reproducing.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Beavers create dams and lodges, changing the ecosystems of the valleys around them.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Earthworms, as Darwin noted, improve the topsoil in which they live by incorporating organic matter.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Humans have constructed extensive civilizations with cities in environments as varied as the Arctic and hot deserts.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] In all three cases, the construction and maintenance of ecological niches helps drive the continued selection of the genes of these animals, in an environment that the animals have modified.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Some traits do not appear to be adaptive as they have a neutral or deleterious effect on fitness in the current environment.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Another possibility is that a trait may have been adaptive at some point in an organism's evolutionary history, but a change in habitats caused what used to be an adaptation to become unnecessary or even maladapted.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Many organisms have vestigial organs, which are the remnants of fully functional structures in their ancestors.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] As a result of changes in lifestyle the organs became redundant, and are either not functional or reduced in functionality.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Since any structure represents some kind of cost to the general economy of the body, an advantage may accrue from their elimination once they are not functional.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Examples: wisdom teeth in humans; the loss of pigment and functional eyes in cave fauna; the loss of structure in endoparasites.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] If a population cannot move or change sufficiently to preserve its long-term viability, then it will become extinct, at least in that locale.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The species may or may not survive in other locales.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Species extinction occurs when the death rate over the entire species exceeds the birth rate for a long enough period for the species to disappear.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] It was an observation of Van Valen that groups of species tend to have a characteristic and fairly regular rate of extinction.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The first stage in the evolution of life on earth is often hypothesized to be the RNA world in which short self-replicating RNA molecules proliferated before the evolution of DNA and proteins.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] By this hypothesis, life started when RNA chains began to self-replicate, initiating the three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation of type, and competition for resources.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The fitness of an RNA replicator (its per capita rate of increase) would likely have been a function of its intrinsic adaptive capacities, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and the availability of resources.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The three primary adaptive capacities may have been: (1) replication with moderate fidelity, giving rise to heritability while allowing variation of type, (2) resistance to decay, and (3) acquisition of resources.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] These adaptive capacities would have been determined by the folded configurations of the RNA replicators resulting from their nucleotide sequences.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] In his biology, Aristotle introduced teleology to describe the adaptedness of organisms, but without accepting the supernatural intention built into Plato's thinking, which Aristotle rejected.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] Modern biologists continue to face the same difficulty.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] On the one hand, adaptation is purposeful: natural selection chooses what works and eliminates what does not.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] On the other hand, biologists by and large reject conscious purpose in evolution.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adaptation] The dilemma gave rise to a famous joke by the evolutionary biologist Haldane: "Teleology is like a mistress to a biologist: he cannot live without her but he's unwilling to be seen with her in public.'" David Hull commented that Haldane's mistress "has become a lawfully wedded wife.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The zoo houses over 3,000 animals comprising 250 native and exotic species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The zoo's most recent enclosures are in the second phase of the South-East Asia exhibit, known as Immersion, providing visitors with the experience of walking through the jungle, with Sumatran tigers and Sumatran orangutans seemingly within reach.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Five buildings within the zoo have been listed as state heritage places on the South Australian Heritage Register, including the front entrance on Frome Road and the former Elephant House.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The zoo is also a botanical garden and the grounds contain significant exotic and native flora, including a Moreton Bay fig planted in 1877.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The zoo is notably home to the Southern Hemisphere's largest giant panda centre, which opened in December 2009.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] It is home to two pandas called Xing Qiu and Yi Lan, who arrived in 2024 to replace Wang Wang and Funi who lived at the zoo until November 2024.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Wang Wang and Funi were notorious for their failed breeding attempts.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Xing Qiu and Yi Lan live as a male and female pair, alongside two Red pandas called Ravi and Maiya.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Adelaide Zoo opened on 23 May 1883, occupying 6.5 hectares (16 acres) (now 8 hectares (20 acres)) of land granted by the government.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] It was founded by the South Australian Acclimatization and Zoological Society.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The society later became the Royal Zoological Society of South Australia after a royal charter was granted by King George VI in 1937.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The first director of the zoo, from 1882 to 1893, was R.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Minchin from 1893 to 1934, and grandson R.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Another grandson, Alfred Keith Minchin ran the private Koala Farm in the North Parklands from 1936 to 1960.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The surplus koalas were set free on Kangaroo Island.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] In the mid-twentieth century the zoo was involved in the export of live birds, with 99% of Australia's exports of live native birds, mainly finches and parrots for aviculture, passing through either Adelaide or Taronga (Sydney).
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] At a time when the need for conservation of Australia's native birds, and control of their trade was becoming increasingly apparent, South Australia lagged behind other states in passing appropriate legislation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] In 1963, the government launched an investigation into the zoo's improper record-keeping of these birds.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The new director of the zoo, William Gasking, was quickly dismissed through the power exerted by the Zoo Council president, Fred Basse, due to Gasking's attempts to address animal health and safety at the zoo.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] When Basse retired, the trade in birds dropped to one tenth of what it had been two years before.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Since then, the zoo's administration has been restructured and the zoo has regained public credibility and scientific status.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The modern zoo has moved away from the traditional housing of species separately in pairs.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Now species are grouped together as they would be in the wild, in exhibits that are carefully planned according to region.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Enclosures have been designed with the needs of the animals in mind, providing a more natural habitat, which also serves an educational purpose for visitors.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Although some of the zoo's heritage listed enclosures, such as the Elephant House that was built in 1900, have been retained, they are no longer used to house animals.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The Elephant House now has educational signs.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The last elephant housed at the Adelaide Zoo, Samorn, was moved to Monarto in 1991, where she died three years later.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The flamingo exhibit was opened in 1885, and is one of the few to have remained in the same position to date.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Originally it was stocked with ten flamingos, most of which died during a drought in 1915.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] In 2014, one of two surviving greater flamingos in the exhibit, thought to be the oldest in the world at 83 years of age, died.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The remaining Chilean flamingo at Adelaide zoo, the last flamingo in Australia, which arrived in 1948, was humanely euthanised on 6 April 2018.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The reptile house opened in 1985 and was expanded in 1993.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The giant panda exhibit and Bamboo Forest opened in 2009.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] This replaced the former "South America Section" and ungulate paddocks.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The former great ape compound behind the administration building was demolished and replaced by an education centre and envirodome in 2008-2009.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] In 2010, the main entrance was relocated off Frome Road in place of the hoofed animal yards, which were demolished.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The famous polychrome masonry and cast-iron gates of the original entry, built in 1883 and restored in 1992, have been preserved.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The zoo's restaurant is located in a brick building that was originally a monkey house.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] It was constructed in 1891, converted to a kiosk in 1936, and renovated in 1989.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The zoo has a particular focus on species from the Gondwana "supercontinent" which later broke up into South America, India, Africa, Australia and South East Asia.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The botanic similarities between the regions are featured in the zoo's main exhibits, which include a South East Asian Rainforest, and Australian Rainforest Wetlands walk-through aviary.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The South East Asian precinct combined Malayan tapir (the last zoo in Australia to keep them, until 2026) and dusky leaf monkeys in a shared exhibit together.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Other exhibits are immersed next to each-other such as those for northern white-cheeked gibbons and siamangs on neighbouring rainforest lake islands.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Pygmy hippopotamuses, mandrills and eastern black-and-white colobuses are amongst the African species conserved by the zoo.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The South East Asia Exhibit called Immersion was built in two parts.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The first part was finished in 1995 which gave exhibits to animals such as siamangs and sun bears (the latter no longer held by the zoo).
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] In late 2006 most of part two was finished which gave exhibits to Sumatran orangutans, siamangs and Sumatran tigers.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] There is also a large walk-through aviary which takes visitors past the two gibbon islands towards the tiger enclosures.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Adelaide Zoo has long been recognised for its impressive bird collection, but Australia's strict importation and quarantine laws make it unlikely that many exotic species will sustain genetically viable populations, a problem experienced by all zoos in the region.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Importation of birds from overseas has been restricted in Australia since 1943, meaning additions to the exotic bird collection can only come from animals bred in the region or seized illegal imports, such as their hyacinth macaw specimen on exhibit.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] There are similar restrictions on acquiring many mammal species in Australia.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The zoo also has a focus on educational programs.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] There is a selection of "get to know the zoo" type of tours, a large "children's zoo" area, and from April 2009, an educational area for secondary school students and their teachers.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Schools can hire the facility and groups can sleep there, with a member from the zoo supervising.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Also, a new educational area called the Envirodome opened in April 2009.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Night walks, tours and animal research can be done.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] More information on the educational programs can be found on the zoo's web site.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The education building in the northeast corner of the zoo replaced the old ape grottos.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The zoo has continued to modernise, emphasizing immersive habitats that reflect natural ecosystems.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Recent upgrade plans include improved enclosures for African, Asian and South American animals at the zoo as well as Australian native animals; as well as expanded breeding programs for native species like the Western swamp tortoise.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The zoo also supports global conservation through initiatives aiding numerous endangered species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] In 2023, the zoo housed more than 2,500 animals and 250 species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] There were 1,300 animals of 282 species in 1990.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The Envirodome is an interactive visitor experience housed in the old Ape Block along with the Education Centre.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The non-animal exhibits are hands-on and are aimed at the conservation of our environment, hoping to educate the public on simple changes they can make to help the environment.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The building itself has been largely recycled and has a green roof, rain-water fed toilets, hay-bale walls and solar panels.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] In January 1902, a keeper was seriously mauled by a brown bear (a species no longer kept by the zoo), having inadequately secured the animal before entering the enclosure.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The bear was shot by fellow keepers and the man rushed to hospital where he slowly recovered (but lost his right arm and suffered serious other permanent injuries, but lived for another ten and a half years).
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] In September 1909, the *Strand Magazine* reported that a snake had swallowed a rug weighing almost 12 pounds (5.4 kg), and which survived undamaged in the snake's stomach until disgorged almost a month later.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The short article featured a photograph of the disgorged rug which was 5 feet 3 inches (1.60 m) long.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Contemporary (1894) accounts had the size of the rug, which was kept in the enclosure for the boa constrictor's comfort, at 7 by 6 feet (2.1 m × 1.8 m), and after disgorgement weighed 5.5 pounds (2.5 kg), dried.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] In February 1920, a keeper was hosing the front of the polar bear enclosure (the species no longer kept by the zoo) when one of the bears reached through the bars and grabbed the hose pulling the keeper forward and mauling him, severing his arm above the elbow.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Minchin, the zoo director, and other staff intervened and freed the man who was then rushed to the hospital where he died two days later from his injuries.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] In 1985, two men broke in and killed 64 animals.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] In 2005, a boy was impaled when he tried to jump the spiked fence with his friends at night.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] On 30 October 2008, a 78-year-old blind male greater flamingo named "Greater" was beaten, allegedly by a group of teenagers.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Four teenagers were charged after visitors reported an incident to zoo staff.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The flamingo was left "extremely stressed".
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] "Greater", the last greater flamingo in Australia, died on 30 January 2014 at the estimated age of 83.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] On Mother's Day 2009, the female orangutan, Karta, built an escape route out of plant material and tripped the hot wires with a stick.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] After a short while on the "outside" she dropped back into the exhibit with no harm done.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] On 12 August 2022, a newly arrived red panda, Ravi, escaped from its enclosure, before being located in a tree at the Botanic Park on 14 August.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The red panda was tranquilised after keepers failed to entice it down with food.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] On 11 October 2022, it was reported that Zoos SA was investigating the deaths of seven female quokkas and two yellow-footed rock wallabies during September.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The cause of their deaths was believed to be plant toxicity.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The last captive Javan rhino was displayed at the Adelaide Zoo as an Indian rhinoceros due to the lack of knowledge about this species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] The last American beaver at the zoo died in July 2010 and was the last beaver to be held at any zoo (or anywhere) in Australia.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Miss C, the last Hoffmann's two-toed sloth in Australia and the oldest in the world died in June 2017 aged 43.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Wang Wang and Fu Ni, two giant pandas, were on loan to Adelaide Zoo from 2009 to 2024, as part of a conservation program to protect endangered wildlife.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Yiray the quokka, one of the Australia-native threatened species at the Adelaide Zoo, gave birth to a baby in March 2022.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Snow White, more commonly known as Snowy, is the world's first and only known “white meerkat”.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] She was born at Adelaide Zoo in September 2010, and began to develop white fur and skin in late 2012; veterinarians eventually diagnosed her with vitiligo.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Prior to 2016 she was named Michael Jackson, after the late pop singer who had been afflicted with the same condition during his lifetime.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] She and the seven brothers she shared an enclosure with would later be renamed after the titular characters of Walt Disney's 1937 animated film *Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Apart from requiring sunscreen and a shadier enclosure to protect her skin from sun damage, Snowy's vitiligo appears to have had minimal effect on her quality of life.
[src:acclimatisation-society/adelaide-zoo] Unfortunately, Snowy was euthanized on October 30th 2024, suffering from age-related health issues at the age of 14.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Alfred Newton was born near Geneva in Switzerland, the fifth son of William Newton of Elveden Hall in Suffolk, Member of Parliament (MP) for Ipswich; his mother Elizabeth (1789–1843) was the daughter of Richard Slater Milnes, MP for York.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] The family wealth was founded on sugar plantations in the Caribbean, where Alfred's grandfather Samuel Newton had a plantation in St Kitts, and a property in St Croix.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] William Newton returned to England in 1813, purchasing the property of Elveden, near Thetford from the Earl of Albemarle.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Elveden (pronounced and sometimes spelt 'Eldon') was built in 1770 by Admiral Augustus Keppel.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] After the Newtons left, Elveden Hall and its estate were bought by Prince Duleep Singh in 1863, and later by the Guinness family (Earl of Iveagh).
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] In 1828 the Newton family made a trip to Italy, and on the way back Alfred was born on 11 June 1829 at Les Délices, a chateau near Geneva.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] He suffered an accident when about five or six, which left him somewhat lame in one leg.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] He went to school in 1844, attending Mr.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Walker's school at Stetchworth near Newmarket.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] He kept birds in cages and looked after other animals from a young age.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] As a youth Newton shot game birds – black or red grouse, common pheasant, partridge.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Those included the great bustard (*Otis tarda*), Montagu's harrier (*Circus pygargus*), ravens, buzzards (*Buteo* sp.), redpolls, wrynecks (*Jynx*), which are small woodpeckers that specialise in feeding on ants.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] "The vast warrens of the 'Breck', the woods and water-meadows of the valley of the Little Ouse, and the neighbouring Fenland made an ideal training-ground for a naturalist".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] This enthusiasm Newton shared with his younger brother Edward: the two carried out bird observation when they were together and corresponded when they were apart.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] In 1846 Newton went to a tutor in Biggleswade for a few months, and in 1848 he entered Magdalene College, Cambridge.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] He took a particular interest in zoology and corresponded with many ornithologists of the time.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] A meeting with John Wolley at Cambridge in 1851 made them lifelong friends.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] He spent the rest of his life at Magdalene, and never married.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] A fall later in life, when he was on a trip to Heligoland, further crippled him, and he then walked with the aid of two sticks, instead of one, as formerly.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] "From a three-legged, he has become a four-legged man" commented a friend.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Newton died on 7 June 1907 of heart failure at the Old Lodge in Magdalene.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] He is buried in the Parish of the Ascension Burial Ground in Cambridge.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] In 1853 he was awarded the Drury Travelling Fellowship of Magdalene College, but he took it up only in 1855, when the grant became available.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Between 1855 and 1864 he visited many parts of the world, including Lapland, Iceland, Spitsbergen, the West Indies and North America.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] In 1858 he made a trip to Iceland with John Wolley with the hope of rediscovering the great auk.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Shortly after their return Wolley died, and at the suggestion of P.L.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Sclater Newton wrote up Wolley's notes and catalogued his collection in *Ootheca Wolleyana,* which was published in four parts from 1864 to 1907.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] In 1866 he became the first Professor of Zoology and Comparative Anatomy at Cambridge, a position which he retained until his death.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] His portrait still hangs in the library of the University's Department of Zoology.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Newton was also a founding editor of the *Journal of Anatomy and Physiology* in 1867.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] He was one of the few British Professors of Zoology of his time in whose appointment Huxley did not have a hand.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Both Darwin and Huxley declined to support his application, on the grounds that his interests and publications were too narrowly focused on ornithology.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] The procedure was for candidates to *canvass for votes* (presumably amongst the MAs of the University).
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] The result of the poll was Newton 110; Dr Drosier 82.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Newton was one of the first zoologists to accept and champion the views of Charles Darwin, and his early lecture courses as professor were on evolution and zoogeography.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Newton was a leader in founding the British Ornithologists' Union in 1858, and its quarterly journal, the *Ibis* in 1859.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] He wrote several books including *Zoology* (1872) and *A Dictionary of Birds* (1893–1896).
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] He contributed memoirs to scientific societies, and edited the *Ibis* (1865–1870), the *Zoological Record* (1870–1872), and Yarrell's *British Birds* (1871–1882).
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] His services to ornithology and zoogeography were recognized by the Royal Society in 1900, when it awarded him the Royal Medal.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Newton spent some time studying the vanishing birds of the Mascarene Islands, from where his brother Sir Edward Newton sent him specimens.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] These included the dodo on Mauritius and the solitaire on Rodrigues, both already extinct.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] In 1872 he described what is now known as Newton's parakeet which lived on Rodrigues before going extinct in 1875.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] The specific epithet of *Genyornis newtoni*, a prehistoric bird described in 1896 by Edward Charles Stirling and A.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] He is also remembered in the name of a hamster, *Mesocricetus newtoni*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Newton's interest in extinct bird species such as the dodo, great auk and great bustard led him to work towards the protection of birds.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] He influenced the legislation of the Sea Birds Preservation Act 1869.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Newton was a prominent supporter and member of the Society for the Protection of Birds (later, 1903, the RSPB) from its inception in 1889, and carried on a long campaign to influence women against the fashion of adorning their hats with the flight feathers of raptors and other fine birds.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] His letters to *The Times* and addresses to the British Association for the Advancement of Science meetings on this subject were regularly reprinted as pamphlets by the Society.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Newton determined that extinction cause by human actions was different from extinction resulting from natural processes including evolution.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] He made efforts to clarify that his motivations for conservation were scientific and that these were distinct from sentiments influenced by earlier movements against animal cruelty and vivisection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] One of his most successful works was a series of investigations into the *Desirability of establishing a 'Close-time' for the preservation of indigenous animals*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] These were instigated and published by the British Association between 1872 and 1903, leading towards the present-day legislation concerning the closed seasons for game fish, shell-fish, birds and mammals (Game laws).
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] The basic concept, as is now well known, is to protect animals during their breeding season so as to prevent the stock from being brought close to extinction.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] The Cambridge University Museum of Zoology contains a significant amount of material from Newton, including specimens collected in Madagascar, Polynesia, South America and the Caribbean, eggs, books and correspondence.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Only four days after the publication of the famous 1858 paper, and one day after he read it, Newton started to apply Darwin's and Wallace's idea to various problems in ornithology.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Newton did not see evolutionary theory as being in conflict with his religion.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] He maintained a regular attendance at church and held deeply conservative views.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Evolutionary theory was, for him, applicable outside of humans.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] The British Association annual meeting for 1860, held in the University Museum in Oxford, was the location for one of the most important public debates in 19th century biology.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Newton was present and left a record of what happened in a letter to his brother Edward.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] A letter, dated 25 July 1860, provides an account of the debate.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Newton was also present at the Cambridge meeting of the British Association two years later.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Ever since 1857 when Richard Owen presented (to the Linnean Society) his view that man was marked off from all other mammals by possessing features of the brain peculiar to the genus *Homo*, Huxley had been on his trail.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] The issue had been debated at the British Association in 1860 and 1861 (Manchester).
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] At the 1862 Cambridge meeting Huxley arranged for his friend William Flower to give a public dissection to show that the same structures were indeed present, not only in apes, but in monkeys also.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-newton] Flower stood up and said "I happen to have in my pocket a monkey's brain" — and produced the object in question!
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace did extensive fieldwork, starting in the Amazon River basin.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He was considered the 19th century's leading expert on the geographical distribution of animal species, and is sometimes called the "father of biogeography", or more specifically of zoogeography.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace was one of the leading evolutionary thinkers of the 19th century, working on warning coloration in animals and reinforcement (sometimes known as the Wallace effect), a way that natural selection could contribute to speciation by encouraging the development of barriers against hybridisation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1864 he was the first to propose that during the later stages of human evolution natural selection would have primarily acted on mental faculties rather than on the physical form.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace's 1904 book *Man's Place in the Universe* was the first serious attempt by a biologist to evaluate the likelihood of life on other planets.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He also had a scientific interest in the possibly of life on Mars.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Aside from scientific work, he was a social activist, critical of what he considered to be the unjust social and economic systems of 19th-century Britain and later in life became an active socialist.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] His advocacy of spiritualism and mind–body dualism strained his relationship with other scientists.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He was one of the first prominent scientists to raise concerns over the environmental impact of human activity.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He wrote prolifically on both scientific and social issues; his account of his adventures and observations during his explorations in Southeast Asia, *The Malay Archipelago*, was first published in 1869.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] It continues to be both popular and highly regarded.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Alfred Russel Wallace was born on 8 January 1823 in Llanbadoc, Monmouthshire.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He was the eighth of nine children born to Mary Anne Wallace (née Greenell) and Thomas Vere Wallace.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] His mother was English, while his father was of Scottish ancestry.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] His family claimed a connection to William Wallace, a leader of Scottish forces during the Wars of Scottish Independence in the 13th century.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace's father graduated in law but never practised it.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He owned some income-generating property, but bad investments and failed business ventures resulted in a steady deterioration of the family's financial position.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace's mother was from a middle-class family of Hertford, to which place his family moved when Wallace was five years old.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He attended Hertford Grammar School until 1837, when he reached the age of 14, the normal leaving age for a pupil not going on to university.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace then moved to London to board with his older brother John, a 19-year-old apprentice builder.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] This was a stopgap measure until William, his oldest brother, was ready to take him on as an apprentice surveyor.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] While in London, Alfred attended lectures and read books at the London Mechanics Institute.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Here he was exposed to the radical political ideas of the Welsh social reformer Robert Owen and of the English-born political theorist Thomas Paine.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He left London in 1837 to live with William and work as his apprentice for six years.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] They moved repeatedly to different places in Mid-Wales.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Then at the end of 1839, they moved to Kington, Herefordshire, near the Welsh border, before eventually settling at Neath in Wales.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Between 1840 and 1843, Wallace worked as a land surveyor in the countryside of the west of England and Wales.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] The natural history of his surroundings aroused his interest; from 1841 he collected flowers and plants as an amateur botanist.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] One result of Wallace's early travels is a modern controversy about his nationality.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Since he was born in Monmouthshire, some sources have considered him to be Welsh.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Other historians have questioned this because neither of his parents were Welsh, his family only briefly lived in Monmouthshire, the Welsh people Wallace knew in his childhood considered him to be English, and because he consistently referred to himself as English rather than Welsh.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] One Wallace scholar has stated that the most reasonable interpretation is therefore that he was an Englishman born in Wales.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1843 Wallace's father died, and a decline in demand for surveying meant William's business no longer had work available.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] For a short time Wallace was unemployed, then early in 1844 he was engaged by the Collegiate School in Leicester to teach drawing, mapmaking, and surveying.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He had already read George Combe's *The Constitution of Man*, and after Spencer Hall lectured on mesmerism, Wallace as well as some of the older pupils tried it out.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace spent many hours at the town library in Leicester; he read Thomas Robert Malthus's *An Essay on the Principle of Population*, Alexander von Humboldt's *Personal Narrative*, Charles Lyell's *Principles of Geology* and Charles Darwin's *The Voyage of the* Beagle.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] One evening Wallace met the entomologist Henry Walter Bates, who was 19 years old, and had published an 1843 paper on beetles in *The Zoologist*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He befriended Wallace and started him collecting insects.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] When Wallace's brother William died in March 1845, Wallace left his teaching position to assume control of his brother's firm in Neath, but his brother John and he were unable to make the business work.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] After a few months, he found work as a civil engineer for a nearby firm that was working on a survey for a proposed railway in the Vale of Neath.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace's work on the survey was largely outdoors in the countryside, allowing him to indulge his new passion for collecting insects.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace persuaded his brother John to join him in starting another architecture and civil engineering firm.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] It carried out projects including the design of a building for the Neath Mechanics' Institute, founded in 1843.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] During this period, he exchanged letters with Bates about books.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] By the end of 1845, Wallace was convinced by Robert Chambers's anonymously published treatise on progressive development, *Vestiges of the Natural History of Creation*, but he found Bates was more critical.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] William Jevons, the founder of the Neath institute, was impressed by Wallace and persuaded him to give lectures there on science and engineering.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In the autumn of 1846, Wallace and his brother John purchased a cottage near Neath, where they lived with their mother and sister Fanny.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Inspired by the chronicles of earlier and contemporary travelling naturalists, Wallace decided to travel abroad.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] They therefore engaged as their agent Samuel Stevens who would advertise and arrange sales to institutions and private collectors, for a commission of 20% on sales plus 5% on despatching freight and remittances of money.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1848, Wallace and Bates left for Brazil aboard the *Mischief*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] They intended to collect insects and other animal specimens in the Amazon rainforest for their private collections, selling the duplicates to museums and collectors back in Britain to fund the trip.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace hoped to gather evidence of the transmutation of species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Bates and he spent most of their first year collecting near Belém, then explored inland separately, occasionally meeting to discuss their findings.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1849, they were briefly joined by another young explorer, the botanist Richard Spruce, along with Wallace's younger brother Herbert.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Herbert soon left (dying two years later from yellow fever), but Spruce, like Bates, would spend over ten years collecting in South America.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace spent four years exploring the Amazon river and its tributary the Rio Negro, collecting specimens and making notes on the peoples and languages he encountered as well as the geography, flora, and fauna..
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace spent August 1850 through May 1852 on the Rio Negro using his surveying skills to chart it and its tributary, the Uaupés, with sextant and compass.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace ascended the Uaupés all the way into Colombia.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] On 12 July 1852, Wallace embarked for the UK on the brig *Helen*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] After 25 days at sea, the ship's cargo caught fire, and the crew was forced to abandon ship.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] All the specimens Wallace had on the ship, mostly collected during the last, and most interesting, two years of his trip, were lost.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He managed to save a few notes and pencil sketches, but little else.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace and the crew spent ten days in an open boat before being picked up by the brig *Jordeson*, which was sailing from Cuba to London.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] The *Jordeson*'s provisions were strained by the unexpected passengers, but after a difficult passage on short rations, the ship reached its destination on 1 October 1852.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] The lost collection had been insured for £200 by Stevens.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] After his return to Britain, Wallace spent 18 months in London living on the insurance payment, and selling a few specimens that had been shipped home.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] During this period, despite having lost almost all the notes from his South American expedition, he wrote six academic papers (including "On the Monkeys of the Amazon") and two books, *Palm Trees of the Amazon and Their Uses* and *Travels on the Amazon*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] At the same time, he made connections with several other British naturalists.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Bates and others were collecting in the Amazon area, Wallace was more interested in new opportunities in the Malay Archipelago as demonstrated by the travel writings of Ida Laura Pfeiffer, and valuable insect specimens she collected which Stevens sold as her agent.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In March 1853 Wallace wrote to Sir James Brooke, Rajah of Sarawak, who was then in London, and who arranged assistance in Sarawak for Wallace.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In June Wallace wrote to Murchison at the Royal Geographical Society (RGS) for support, proposing to again fund his exploring entirely from sale of duplicate collections.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He later recalled that, while researching in the insect-room of the British Museum, he was introduced to Darwin and they "had a few minutes' conversation." After presenting a paper and a large map of the Rio Negro to the RGS, Wallace was elected a Fellow of the society on 27 February 1854.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Free passage arranged on Royal Navy ships was stalled by the Crimean War, but eventually the RGS funded first class travel by P&O steamships.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace and a young assistant, Charles Allen, embarked at Southampton on 4 March 1854.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] After the overland journey to Suez and another change of ship at Ceylon they disembarked at Singapore on 19 April 1854.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] From 1854 to 1862, Wallace travelled around the islands of the Malay Archipelago or East Indies (now Singapore, Malaysia and Indonesia).
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] His main objective "was to obtain specimens of natural history, both for my private collection and to supply duplicates to museums and amateurs".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In addition to Allen, he "generally employed one or two, and sometimes three Malay servants" as assistants, and paid large numbers of local people at various places to bring specimens.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] His total was 125,660 specimens, most of which were insects including more than 83,000 beetles.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Several thousand of the specimens represented species new to science.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Overall, more than thirty men worked for him at some stage as full-time paid collectors.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He also hired guides, porters, cooks and boat crews, so well over 100 individuals worked for him.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] After collecting expeditions to Bukit Timah Hill in Singapore, and to Malacca, Wallace and Allen reached Sarawak in October 1854, and were welcomed at Kuching by Sir James Brooke's (then) heir Captain John Brooke.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace hired a Malay named Ali as a general servant and cook, and spent the early 1855 wet season in a small Dyak house at the foot of Mount Santubong, overlooking a branch outlet of the Sarawak River.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He read about species distribution, notes on Pictets's Palaeontology, and wrote his "Sarawak Paper".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In March he moved to the Simunjon coal-works, operated by the Borneo Company under Ludvig Verner Helms, and supplemented collecting by paying workers a cent for each insect.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] A specimen of the previously unknown gliding tree frog *Rhacophorus nigropalmatus* (now called Wallace's flying frog) came from a Chinese workman who told Wallace that it glided down.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Local people also assisted with shooting orangutans.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] They spent time with Sir James, then in February 1856 Allen chose to stay on with the missionaries at Kuching.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] On reaching Singapore in May 1856, Wallace hired a bird-skinner.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] With Ali as cook, they collected for two days on Bali, then from 17 June to 30 August on Lombok.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In December 1856, Darwin had written to contacts worldwide to get specimens for his continuing research into variation under domestication.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] At Lombok's port city, Ampanam, Wallace wrote telling his agent, Stevens, about specimens shipped, including a domestic duck variety "for Mr.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Stevens arranged publication of relevant paragraphs in the January 1857 issue of *The Zoologist*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] After further investigation, the zoogeographical boundary eventually became known as the Wallace Line.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Ali became Wallace's most trusted assistant, a skilled collector and researcher.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace collected and preserved the delicate insect specimens, while most of the birds were collected and prepared by his assistants; of those, Ali collected and prepared around 5000.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] While exploring the archipelago, Wallace refined his thoughts about evolution, and had his famous insight on natural selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1858 he sent an article outlining his theory to Darwin; it was published, along with a description of Darwin's theory, that same year.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Accounts of Wallace's studies and adventures were eventually published in 1869 as *The Malay Archipelago*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] This became one of the most popular books of scientific exploration of the 19th century, and has never been out of print.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] It was praised by scientists such as Darwin (to whom the book was dedicated), by Lyell, and by non-scientists such as the novelist Joseph Conrad.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Conrad called the book his "favorite bedside companion" and used information from it for several of his novels, especially *Lord Jim*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] A set of 80 bird skeletons Wallace collected in Indonesia are held in the Cambridge University Museum of Zoology, and described as of exceptional historical significance.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1862, Wallace returned to Britain, where he moved in with his sister Fanny Sims and her husband Thomas.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] While recovering from his travels, Wallace organised his collections and gave numerous lectures about his adventures and discoveries to scientific societies such as the Zoological Society of London.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Later that year, he visited Darwin at Down House, and became friendly with both Lyell and the philosopher Herbert Spencer.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] During the 1860s, Wallace wrote papers and gave lectures defending natural selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He corresponded with Darwin about topics including sexual selection, warning coloration, and the possible effect of natural selection on hybridisation and the divergence of species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1865, he began investigating spiritualism.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] After a year of courtship, Wallace became engaged in 1864 to a young woman whom, in his autobiography, he would only identify as Miss L.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Miss L. was the daughter of Lewis Leslie who played chess with Wallace, but to Wallace's great dismay, she broke off the engagement.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace had been introduced to Mitten through the botanist Richard Spruce, who had befriended Wallace in Brazil and who was a friend of Annie Mitten's father, William Mitten, an expert on mosses.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1872, Wallace built the Dell, a house of concrete, on land he leased in Grays in Essex, where he lived until 1876.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In the late 1860s and 1870s, Wallace was very concerned about the financial security of his family.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] While he was in the Malay Archipelago, the sale of specimens had brought in a considerable amount of money, which had been carefully invested by the agent who sold the specimens for Wallace.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] On his return to the UK, Wallace made a series of bad investments in railways and mines that squandered most of the money, and he found himself badly in need of the proceeds from the publication of *The Malay Archipelago*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Despite assistance from his friends, he was never able to secure a permanent salaried position such as a curatorship in a museum.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] To remain financially solvent, Wallace worked grading government examinations, wrote 25 papers for publication between 1872 and 1876 for various modest sums, and was paid by Lyell and Darwin to help edit some of their works.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1876, Wallace needed a £500 advance from the publisher of *The Geographical Distribution of Animals* to avoid having to sell some of his personal property.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Darwin was very aware of Wallace's financial difficulties and lobbied long and hard to get Wallace awarded a government pension for his lifetime contributions to science.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] When the £200 annual pension was awarded in 1881, it helped to stabilise Wallace's financial position by supplementing the income from his writings.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1881, Wallace was elected as the first president of the newly formed Land Nationalisation Society.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In the next year, he published a book, *Land Nationalisation; Its Necessity and Its Aims*, on the subject.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1889, Wallace read *Looking Backward* by Edward Bellamy and declared himself a socialist, despite his earlier foray as a speculative investor.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace opposed eugenics, an idea supported by other prominent 19th-century evolutionary thinkers, on the grounds that contemporary society was too corrupt and unjust to allow any reasonable determination of who was fit or unfit.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace wrote repeatedly on the dangers and wastefulness of militarism.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace criticised the UK's free trade policies for the negative impact they had on working-class people.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1898, He wrote a paper advocating a pure paper money system, not backed by silver or gold, which impressed the economist Irving Fisher so much that he dedicated his 1920 book *Stabilizing the Dollar* to Wallace.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace wrote in support of women's suffrage.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1898, Wallace published *The Wonderful Century: Its Successes and Its Failures*, about developments in the 19th century.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace continued his social activism for the rest of his life, publishing the book *The Revolt of Democracy* just weeks before his death.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1880, he published *Island Life* as a sequel to *The Geographic Distribution of Animals*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In November 1886, Wallace began a ten-month trip to the United States to give a series of popular lectures.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Most of the lectures were on Darwinism (evolution through natural selection), but he also gave speeches on biogeography, spiritualism, and socio-economic reform.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] During the trip, he was reunited with his brother John who had emigrated to California years before.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He spent a day touring Yosemite in the company of John Muir.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Years later Muir would credit his conversation with Wallace with sparking his interest in visiting the Amazon basin.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He met many other prominent American naturalists and viewed their collections.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] His 1889 book *Darwinism* used information he collected on his American trip and information he had compiled for the lectures.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] On 7 November 1913, Wallace died at home, aged 90, in the country house he called Old Orchard, which he had built a decade earlier.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] His death was widely reported in the press.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] *The New York Times* called him "the last of the giants [belonging] to that wonderful group of intellectuals composed of Darwin, Huxley, Spencer, Lyell, Owen, and other scientists, whose daring investigations revolutionized and evolutionized the thought of the century".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Some of Wallace's friends suggested that he be buried in Westminster Abbey, but his wife followed his wishes and had him buried in the small cemetery at Broadstone, Dorset.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Several prominent British scientists formed a committee to have a medallion of Wallace placed in Westminster Abbey near where Darwin had been buried.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] The medallion was unveiled on 1 November 1915.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace began his career as a travelling naturalist already believing in the transmutation of species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The concept had been advocated by Jean-Baptiste Lamarck, Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire, Erasmus Darwin, and Robert Grant, among others.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It was widely discussed, but not generally accepted by leading naturalists, and was considered to have radical, even revolutionary connotations.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Prominent anatomists and geologists such as Georges Cuvier, Richard Owen, Adam Sedgwick, and Lyell attacked transmutation vigorously.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It has been suggested that Wallace accepted the idea of the transmutation of species in part because he was always inclined to favour radical ideas in politics, religion and science, and because he was unusually open to marginal, even fringe, ideas in science.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace was profoundly influenced by Robert Chambers's *Vestiges of the Natural History of Creation*, a controversial work of popular science published anonymously in 1844.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It advocated an evolutionary origin for the Solar System, the Earth, and living things.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace wrote to Henry Bates in 1845 describing it as "an ingenious hypothesis strongly supported by some striking facts and analogies, but which remains to be proven by ... more research".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace planned fieldwork to test the evolutionary hypothesis that closely related species should inhabit neighbouring territories.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] During his work in the Amazon basin, he came to realise that geographical barriers—such as the Amazon and its major tributaries—often separated the ranges of closely allied species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He included these observations in his 1853 paper "On the Monkeys of the Amazon".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Near the end of the paper he asked the question, "Are very closely allied species ever separated by a wide interval of country?".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] For sometime Wallace had been compiling notes for an argument against the concept of new species being introduced through progressive creationism found in Charles Lyell's *Principles of Geology*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] This was Lyell's rebuttal to transmutational ideas.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] When Wallace read an 1854 paper written by Edward Forbes that proposed an even more quasi-mystical form of progressive creationism he decided to write a response.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In February 1855, while working in Sarawak on the island of Borneo, Wallace wrote "On the Law which has Regulated the Introduction of New Species".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The paper was published in the *Annals and Magazine of Natural History* in September 1855.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In this paper, he discussed observations of the geographic and geologic distribution of both living and fossil species, a field that became biogeography.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] This paper foreshadowed the momentous paper he would write three years later.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The paper challenged Lyell's belief that species were immutable.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Although Darwin had written to him in 1842 expressing support for transmutation, Lyell had continued to be strongly opposed to the idea.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Around the start of 1856, he told Darwin about Wallace's paper, as did Edward Blyth who thought it "Good!
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace has, I think put the matter well; and according to his theory the various domestic races of animals have been fairly developed into *species*." Despite this hint, Darwin mistook Wallace's conclusion for the progressive creationism of the time, writing that it was "nothing very new ...
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Uses my simile of tree [but] it seems all creation with him." Lyell was more impressed, and opened a notebook on species in which he grappled with the consequences, particularly for human ancestry.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin had already shown his theory to their mutual friend Joseph Hooker and now, for the first time spelt out the full details of natural selection to Lyell.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Although Lyell could not agree, he urged Darwin to publish to establish priority.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin demurred at first, but began writing up a *species sketch* of his continuing work in May 1856.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] By February 1858, Wallace had been convinced by his biogeographical research in the Malay Archipelago that evolution was real.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He later wrote in his autobiography that the problem was of how species change from one well-marked form to another.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He stated that it was while he was in bed with a fever that he thought about Malthus's idea of positive checks on human population, and had the idea of natural selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] His autobiography says that he was on the island of Ternate at the time; but the evidence of his journal suggests that he was in fact on the island of Gilolo.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] From 1858 to 1861, he rented a house on Ternate from the Dutchman Maarten Dirk van Renesse van Duivenbode, which he used as a base for expeditions to other islands such as Gilolo.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace had once briefly met Darwin, and was one of the correspondents whose observations Darwin used to support his own theories.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Although Wallace's first letter to Darwin has been lost, Wallace carefully kept the letters he received.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The second letter, dated 22 December 1857, said how glad he was that Wallace was theorising about distribution, adding that "without speculation there is no good and original observation" but commented that "I believe I go much further than you".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace believed this and sent Darwin his February 1858 essay, "On the Tendency of Varieties to Depart Indefinitely From the Original Type", asking Darwin to review it and pass it to Charles Lyell if he thought it worthwhile.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Although Wallace had sent several articles for journal publication during his travels through the Malay archipelago, the Ternate essay was in a private letter.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin received the essay on 18 June 1858.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Although the essay did not use Darwin's term "natural selection", it did outline the mechanics of an evolutionary divergence of species from similar ones due to environmental pressures.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In this sense, it was very similar to the theory that Darwin had worked on for 20 years, but had yet to publish.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin sent the manuscript to Charles Lyell with a letter saying "he could not have made a better short abstract!
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's essay was presented to the Linnean Society of London on 1 July 1858, along with excerpts from an essay which Darwin had disclosed privately to Hooker in 1847 and a letter Darwin had written to Asa Gray in 1857.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Communication with Wallace in the far-off Malay Archipelago involved months of delay, so he was not part of this rapid publication.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace accepted the arrangement after the fact, happy that he had been included at all, and never expressed bitterness in public or in private.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin's social and scientific status was far greater than Wallace's, and it was unlikely that, without Darwin, Wallace's views on evolution would have been taken seriously.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Lyell and Hooker's arrangement relegated Wallace to the position of co-discoverer, and he was not the social equal of Darwin or the other prominent British natural scientists.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] All the same, the joint reading of their papers on natural selection associated Wallace with the more famous Darwin.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] This, combined with Darwin's (as well as Hooker's and Lyell's) advocacy on his behalf, would give Wallace greater access to the highest levels of the scientific community.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The reaction to the reading was muted, with the president of the Linnean Society remarking in May 1859 that the year had not been marked by any striking discoveries; but, with Darwin's publication of *On the Origin of Species* later in 1859, its significance became apparent.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] When Wallace returned to the UK, he met Darwin.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Although some of Wallace's opinions in the ensuing years would test Darwin's patience, they remained friends and frequent correspondents for the rest of Darwin's life.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Over the years, a few people have questioned this version of events.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In the early 1980s, two books, one by Arnold Brackman and another by John Langdon Brooks, suggested not only that there had been a conspiracy to rob Wallace of his proper credit, but that Darwin had actually stolen a key idea from Wallace to finish his own theory.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] These claims have been examined and found unconvincing by a number of scholars.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Shipping schedules show that, contrary to these accusations, Wallace's letter could not have been delivered earlier than the date shown in Darwin's letter to Lyell.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] After Wallace returned to England in 1862, he became one of the staunchest defenders of Darwin's *On the Origin of Species*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In an incident in 1863 that particularly pleased Darwin, Wallace published the short paper "Remarks on the Rev.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Haughton's Paper on the Bee's Cell, And on the Origin of Species".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] This rebutted a paper by a professor of geology at the University of Dublin that had sharply criticised Darwin's comments in the *Origin* on how hexagonal honey bee cells could have evolved through natural selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] An even longer defence was an 1867 article in the *Quarterly Journal of Science*, "Creation by Law".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It reviewed George Campbell, the 8th Duke of Argyll's book, *The Reign of Law*, which aimed to refute natural selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] After an 1870 meeting of the British Science Association, Wallace wrote to Darwin complaining that there were "no opponents left who know anything of natural history, so that there are none of the good discussions we used to have".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Explorers in Madagascar had discovered the orchid *Angraecum sesquipedale*, with a sixteen-inch nectary.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin predicted the existence of a moth with a proboscis long enough to pollinate it.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Historians of science have noted that, while Darwin considered the ideas in Wallace's paper to be essentially the same as his own, there were differences.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin emphasised competition between individuals of the same species to survive and reproduce, whereas Wallace emphasised environmental pressures on varieties and species forcing them to become adapted to their local conditions, leading populations in different locations to diverge.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Bowler has suggested that in the paper he mailed to Darwin, Wallace might have been discussing group selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Against this, Malcolm Kottler showed that Wallace was indeed discussing individual variation and selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Others have noted that Wallace appeared to have envisioned natural selection as a kind of feedback mechanism that kept species and varieties adapted to their environment (now called 'stabilizing", as opposed to 'directional' selection).
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] They point to a largely overlooked passage of Wallace's famous 1858 paper, in which he likened "this principle ... [to] the centrifugal governor of the steam engine, which checks and corrects any irregularities".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The cybernetician and anthropologist Gregory Bateson observed in the 1970s that, although writing it only as an example, Wallace had "probably said the most powerful thing that'd been said in the 19th Century".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Bateson revisited the topic in his 1979 book *Mind and Nature: A Necessary Unity*, and other scholars have continued to explore the connection between natural selection and systems theory.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Warning colouration was one of Wallace's contributions to the evolutionary biology of animal colouration.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1867, Darwin wrote to Wallace about a problem in explaining how some caterpillars could have evolved conspicuous colour schemes.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin had come to believe that many conspicuous animal colour schemes were due to sexual selection, but he saw that this could not apply to caterpillars.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace responded that he and Bates had observed that many of the most spectacular butterflies had a peculiar odour and taste, and that he had been told by John Jenner Weir that birds would not eat a certain kind of common white moth because they found it unpalatable.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Since the moth was as conspicuous at dusk as a coloured caterpillar in daylight, it seemed likely that the conspicuous colours served as a warning to predators and thus could have evolved through natural selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] At a later meeting of the Entomological Society, and in a letter published in *Field* magazine, Wallace asked for any evidence anyone might have on the topic.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1869, Weir published data from experiments and observations involving brightly coloured caterpillars that supported Wallace's idea.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace attributed less importance than Darwin to sexual selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] One area where he debated Darwin involved explaining sexual dimorphism in the colouration and nesting behaviour of many bird species where males are more brightly coloured than females.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin attributed this to sexual selection by females between competing males.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In the 1860s Wallace wrote a series of papers that emphasized instead selective pressure from predation for drab colouration in females that spend a lot of time sitting on nests.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In his 1878 book *Tropical Nature and Other Essays*, he wrote extensively about the colouration of animals and plants, and proposed alternative explanations for a number of cases Darwin had attributed to sexual selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He revisited the topic at length in his 1889 book *Darwinism*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1890, he wrote a critical review in *Nature* of his friend Edward Bagnall Poulton's *The Colours of Animals* which supported Darwin on sexual selection, attacking especially Poulton's claims on the "aesthetic preferences of the insect world".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1889, Wallace wrote the book *Darwinism*, which explained and defended natural selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In it, he proposed the hypothesis that natural selection could drive the reproductive isolation of two varieties by encouraging the development of barriers against hybridisation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Thus it might contribute to the development of new species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He suggested the following scenario: When two populations of a species had diverged beyond a certain point, each adapted to particular conditions, hybrid offspring would be less adapted than either parent form and so natural selection would tend to eliminate the hybrids.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Furthermore, under such conditions, natural selection would favour the development of barriers to hybridisation, as individuals that avoided hybrid matings would tend to have more fit offspring, and thus contribute to the reproductive isolation of the two incipient species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] This idea came to be known as the Wallace effect, later called reinforcement.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He was motivated to spell the idea out in detail in 1889 in response to a paper by George Romanes that suggested that natural selection alone was insufficient to explain the separation of incipient species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace had suggested to Darwin that natural selection could play a role in preventing hybridisation in private correspondence as early as 1868, but had not worked it out in detail.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It continues to be a topic of research in evolutionary biology today, with both computer simulation and empirical results supporting its validity.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In January 1864 Wallace presented a paper, "On the Varieties of Man in the Malay Archipelago", to the Ethnological Society of London.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] This paper summarized his ethnological observations during his travels in the East Indies.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace stated that the people in the archipelago could be divided into two groups.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The first were members of what he called the Malay race and the second were members of the Papuan race.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He described the physical, linguistic, and cultural differences between them, and he traced an east west dividing line that separated the 2 groups.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He compared this with the famous dividing line he had discovered between Asian and Australian affiliated faunas, suggesting that the distribution of human races could be explained by the geographical history of a region the same way as the biogeographical distribution of species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] A few weeks later he presented a follow up paper, "The Origin of Human Races and the Antiquity of Man Deduced from the Theory of 'Natural Selection'" to the Anthropological Society of London, applying the theory of natural selection to humankind.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin had not yet publicly addressed the subject, although Thomas Huxley had in *Evidence as to Man's Place in Nature*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace explained the apparent stability of the human stock by pointing to the vast gap in cranial capacities between humans and the great apes.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Unlike some other Darwinists, including Darwin himself, he did not "regard modern primitives as almost filling the gap between man and ape".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He saw the evolution of humans in two stages: achieving a bipedal posture that freed the hands to carry out the dictates of the brain, and the "recognition of the human brain as a totally new factor in the history of life".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace seems to have been the first evolutionist to propose that the human brain effectively made further specialisation of the body unnecessary.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin would treat this idea at length in his 1871 work *The Descent of Man, and Selection in Relation to Sex*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace wrote the paper to address the debate between the supporters of monogenism, the belief that all human races shared a common ancestor and were part of one species, and the supporters of polygenism, who held that different races had separate origins and were different species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's anthropological observations of Native Americans in the Amazon, and especially his time living among the Dayak people of Borneo, had convinced him that human beings were a single species with a common ancestor.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He still felt that natural selection might have continued to act on mental faculties after the development of the different races; and he did not dispute the nearly universal view among European anthropologists of the time that Europeans were intellectually superior to other races.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Charles Lyell wrote to Wallace praising the paper and saying that it had made a major contribution to resolving the dispute between monogenists and polygenists.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] At about the same time, he began to maintain that natural selection could not account for mathematical, artistic, or musical genius, metaphysical musings, or wit and humour.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He stated that something in "the unseen universe of Spirit" had interceded at least three times in history: the creation of life from inorganic matter; the introduction of consciousness in the higher animals; and the generation of the higher mental faculties in humankind.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He believed that the raison d'être of the universe was the development of the human spirit.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Reaction to Wallace's ideas on this topic among leading naturalists at the time varied.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Lyell endorsed Wallace's views on human evolution rather than Darwin's.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's belief that human consciousness could not be entirely a product of purely material causes was shared by a number of prominent intellectuals in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] All the same, many, including Huxley, Hooker, and Darwin himself, were critical of Wallace's views.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] As the historian of science and sceptic Michael Shermer has stated, Wallace's views in this area were at odds with two major tenets of the emerging Darwinian philosophy.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] These were that evolution was not teleological (purpose-driven), and that it was not anthropocentric (human-centred).
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Much later in his life Wallace returned to these themes, that evolution suggested that the universe might have a purpose, and that certain aspects of living organisms might not be explainable in terms of purely materialistic processes.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He set out his ideas in a 1909 magazine article entitled *The World of Life*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace anticipated ideas about design in nature and directed evolution that would arise from religious traditions throughout the 20th century.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In many accounts of the development of evolutionary theory, Wallace is mentioned only in passing as simply being the stimulus to the publication of Darwin's own theory.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In reality, Wallace developed his own distinct evolutionary views which diverged from Darwin's, and was considered by many (especially Darwin) to be a leading thinker on evolution in his day, whose ideas could not be ignored.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] One historian of science has pointed out that, through both private correspondence and published works, Darwin and Wallace exchanged knowledge and stimulated each other's ideas and theories over an extended period.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace is the most-cited naturalist in Darwin's *Descent of Man*, occasionally in strong disagreement.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin and Wallace agreed on the importance of natural selection, and some of the factors responsible for it: competition between species and geographical isolation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] But Wallace believed that evolution had a purpose ("teleology") in maintaining species' fitness to their environment, whereas Darwin hesitated to attribute any purpose to a random natural process.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Scientific discoveries since the 19th century support Darwin's viewpoint, by identifying additional mechanisms and triggers such as mutations triggered by environmental radiation or mutagenic chemicals.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace remained an ardent defender of natural selection for the rest of his life.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] By the 1880s, evolution was widely accepted in scientific circles, but natural selection less so.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's 1889 *Darwinism* was a response to the scientific critics of natural selection.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Of all Wallace's books, it is the most cited by scholarly publications.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1872, at the urging of many of his friends, including Darwin, Philip Sclater, and Alfred Newton, Wallace began research for a general review of the geographic distribution of animals.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Initial progress was slow, in part because classification systems for many types of animals were in flux.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He resumed the work in earnest in 1874 after the publication of a number of new works on classification.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Extending the system developed by Sclater for birds—which divided the earth into six separate geographic regions for describing species distribution—to cover mammals, reptiles and insects as well, Wallace created the basis for the zoogeographic regions in use today.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He discussed the factors then known to influence the current and past geographic distribution of animals within each geographic region.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] These factors included the effects of the appearance and disappearance of land bridges (such as the one currently connecting North America and South America) and the effects of periods of increased glaciation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] When the Isthmus of Panama formed, species crossed it in both directions in the Great American Interchange.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He provided maps showing factors, such as elevation of mountains, depths of oceans, and the character of regional vegetation, that affected the distribution of animals.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He summarised all the known families and genera of the higher animals and listed their known geographic distributions.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The text was organised so that it would be easy for a traveller to learn what animals could be found in a particular location.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The resulting two-volume work, *The Geographical Distribution of Animals*, was published in 1876 and served as the definitive text on zoogeography for the next 80 years.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The book included evidence from the fossil record to discuss the processes of evolution and migration that had led to the geographical distribution of modern species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace was very aware of, and interested in, the mass extinction of megafauna in the late Pleistocene.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In *The Geographical Distribution of Animals* (1876) he wrote, "We live in a zoologically impoverished world, from which all the hugest, and fiercest, and strangest forms have recently disappeared".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He added that he believed the most likely cause for the rapid extinctions was glaciation, but by the time he wrote *World of Life* (1911) he had come to believe those extinctions were "due to man's agency".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1880, Wallace published the book *Island Life* as a sequel to *The Geographical Distribution of Animals*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It surveyed the distribution of both animal and plant species on islands.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace classified islands into oceanic and two types of continental islands.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Oceanic islands, in his view, such as the Galápagos and Hawaiian Islands (then called Sandwich Islands) formed in mid-ocean and never part of any large continent.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Such islands were characterised by a complete lack of terrestrial mammals and amphibians, and their inhabitants (except migratory birds and species introduced by humans) were typically the result of accidental colonisation and subsequent evolution.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Continental islands, in his scheme, were divided into those that were recently separated from a continent (like Britain) and those much less recently (like Madagascar).
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace discussed how that difference affected flora and fauna.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He discussed how isolation affected evolution and how that could result in the preservation of classes of animals, such as the lemurs of Madagascar that were remnants of once widespread continental faunas.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He extensively discussed how changes of climate, particularly periods of increased glaciation, may have affected the distribution of flora and fauna on some islands, and the first portion of the book discusses possible causes of these great ice ages.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] *Island Life* was considered a very important work at the time of its publication.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It was discussed extensively in scientific circles both in published reviews and in private correspondence.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's extensive work in biogeography made him aware of the impact of human activities on the natural world.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He was also impressed by George Perkins Marsh's influential book Man and Nature.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In *Tropical Nature and Other Essays* (1878), citing Marsh, he warned about the dangers of deforestation and soil erosion, especially in tropical climates prone to heavy rainfall.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Noting the complex interactions between vegetation and climate, he warned that the extensive clearing of rainforest for coffee cultivation in Ceylon (now called Sri Lanka) and India would adversely impact the climate in those countries and lead to their impoverishment due to soil erosion.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In *Island Life*, Wallace again mentioned deforestation and invasive species.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] On the impact of European colonisation on the island of Saint Helena, he wrote that the island was "now so barren and forbidding that some persons find it difficult to believe that it was once all green and fertile".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He explained that the soil was protected by the island's vegetation; once that was destroyed, the soil was washed off the steep slopes by heavy tropical rain, leaving "bare rock or sterile clay".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He attributed the "irreparable destruction" to feral goats, introduced in 1513.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The island's forests were further damaged by the "reckless waste" of the East India Company from 1651, which used the bark of valuable redwood and ebony trees for tanning, leaving the wood to rot unused.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's comments on environment grew more urgent later in his career.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He concluded that the Earth was the only planet in the Solar System that could possibly support life, mainly because it was the only one in which water could exist in the liquid phase.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] His treatment of Mars in this book was brief, and in 1907, Wallace returned to the subject with the book *Is Mars Habitable?* to criticise the claims made by the American astronomer Percival Lowell that there were Martian canals built by intelligent beings.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace did months of research, consulted various experts, and produced his own scientific analysis of the Martian climate and atmospheric conditions.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Richard Milner comments that Wallace "effectively debunked Lowell's illusionary network of Martian canals." Wallace became interested in the topic because his anthropocentric philosophy inclined him to believe that man would be unique in the universe.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace was an enthusiast of phrenology.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Early in his career, he experimented with hypnosis, then known as mesmerism, managing to hypnotise some of his students in Leicester.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] When he began these experiments, the topic was very controversial: early experimenters, such as John Elliotson, had been harshly criticised by the medical and scientific establishment.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace drew a connection between his experiences with mesmerism and spiritualism, arguing that one should not deny observations on "a priori grounds of absurdity or impossibility".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace began investigating spiritualism in the summer of 1865, possibly at the urging of his older sister Fanny Sims.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] After reviewing the literature and attempting to test what he witnessed at séances, he came to believe in it.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] For the rest of his life, he remained convinced that at least some séance phenomena were genuine, despite accusations of fraud and evidence of trickery.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] One biographer suggested that the emotional shock when his first fiancée broke their engagement contributed to his receptiveness to spiritualism.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Other scholars have emphasised his desire to find scientific explanations for all phenomena.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1874, Wallace visited the spirit photographer Frederick Hudson.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He declared that a photograph of him with his deceased mother was genuine.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Others reached a different conclusion: Hudson's photographs had previously been exposed as fraudulent in 1872.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's public advocacy of spiritualism and his repeated defence of spiritualist mediums against allegations of fraud in the 1870s damaged his scientific reputation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1875 he published the evidence he believed proved his position in *On Miracles and Modern Spiritualism*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] His attitude permanently strained his relationships with previously friendly scientists such as Henry Bates, Thomas Huxley, and even Darwin.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Others, such as the physiologist William Benjamin Carpenter and zoologist E.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Ray Lankester became publicly hostile to Wallace over the issue.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace was heavily criticised by the press; *The Lancet* was particularly harsh.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] This he is said to have done in an underhanded manner, and I well remember the indignation it gave rise to in the B.A.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Council." Hooker eventually relented and agreed to support the pension request.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1870, a flat-Earth proponent named John Hampden offered a £500 wager (roughly equivalent to £51,000 in 2025) in a magazine advertisement to anyone who could demonstrate a convex curvature in a body of water such as a river, canal, or lake.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace, intrigued by the challenge and short of money at the time, designed an experiment in which he set up two objects along a six-mile (10 km) stretch of canal.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Both objects were at the same height above the water, and he mounted a telescope on a bridge at the same height above the water as well.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] When seen through the telescope, one object appeared higher than the other, showing the curvature of the Earth.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The judge for the wager, the editor of *Field* magazine, declared Wallace the winner, but Hampden refused to accept the result.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He sued Wallace and launched a campaign, which persisted for several years, of writing letters to various publications and to organisations of which Wallace was a member denouncing him as a swindler and a thief.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace won multiple libel suits against Hampden, but the resulting litigation cost Wallace more than the amount of the wager, and the controversy frustrated him for years.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In the early 1880s, Wallace joined the debate over mandatory smallpox vaccination.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace originally saw the issue as a matter of personal liberty; but, after studying statistics provided by anti-vaccination activists, he began to question the efficacy of vaccination.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] At the time, the germ theory of disease was new and far from universally accepted.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Moreover, no one knew enough about the human immune system to understand why vaccination worked.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace discovered instances where supporters of vaccination had used questionable, in a few cases completely false, statistics to support their arguments.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Always suspicious of authority, Wallace suspected that physicians had a vested interest in promoting vaccination, and became convinced that reductions in the incidence of smallpox that had been attributed to vaccination were due to better hygiene and improvements in public sanitation.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Another factor in Wallace's thinking was his belief that, because of the action of natural selection, organisms were in a state of balance with their environment, and that everything in nature, served a useful purpose.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace pointed out that vaccination, which at the time was often unsanitary, could be dangerous.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1890, Wallace gave evidence to a royal commission investigating the controversy.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It found errors in his testimony, including some questionable statistics.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] *The Lancet* averred that Wallace and other activists were being selective in their choice of statistics.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The commission found that smallpox vaccination was effective and should remain compulsory, though they recommended some changes in procedures to improve safety, and that the penalties for people who refused to comply be made less severe.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Years later, in 1898, Wallace wrote a pamphlet, *Vaccination a Delusion; Its Penal Enforcement a Crime*, attacking the commission's findings.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It, in turn, was attacked by *The Lancet*, which stated that it repeated many of the same errors as his evidence given to the commission.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] As a result of his writing, Wallace became a well-known figure both as a scientist and as a social activist, and was often sought out for his views.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He became president of the anthropology section of the British Association in 1866, and of the Entomological Society of London in 1870.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1873.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The British Association elected him as head of its biology section in 1876.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He was elected to the Royal Society in 1893.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He was asked to chair the International Congress of Spiritualists meeting in London in 1898.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He received honorary doctorates and professional honours, such the Royal Society's Royal Medal in 1868 and its Darwin Medal in 1890, and the Order of Merit in 1908.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's fame faded quickly after his death.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] For a long time, he was treated as a relatively obscure figure in the history of science.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Reasons for this lack of attention may have included his modesty, his willingness to champion unpopular causes without regard for his own reputation, and the discomfort of much of the scientific community with some of his unconventional ideas.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The reason that the theory of evolution is popularly credited to Darwin is likely the impact of Darwin's *On the Origin of Species*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Recently, Wallace has become better known, with the publication of at least five book-length biographies and two anthologies of his writings published since 2000.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] A web page dedicated to Wallace scholarship is maintained at Western Kentucky University.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] A collection of his medals, including the Order of Merit, were sold at auction for £273,000 in 2022.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The Natural History Museum, London, co-ordinated commemorative events for the Wallace centenary worldwide in the 'Wallace100' project in 2013.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] On 24 January, his portrait was unveiled in the Main Hall of the museum by Bill Bailey, a fervent admirer.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Bailey further championed Wallace in his 2013 BBC Two series "Bill Bailey's Jungle Hero".
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] On 7 November 2013, the 100th anniversary of Wallace's death, Sir David Attenborough unveiled a statue of Wallace at the museum.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The statue, sculpted by Anthony Smith, was donated by the A.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It depicts Wallace as a young man, collecting in the jungle.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] November 2013 marked the debut of *The Animated Life of A.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace*, a paper-puppet animation film dedicated to Wallace's centennial.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In addition, Bailey unveiled a bust of Wallace, sculpted by Felicity Crawley, in Twyn Square in Usk, Monmouthshire in November 2021.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Commemorations of the 200th anniversary of Wallace's birth celebrated during the course of 2023 range from naturalist walk events to scientific congresses and presentations.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] A Harvard Museum of Natural History event in April 2023 will also include a mixologist-designed special cocktail to honor Wallace's legacy.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Mount Wallace in California's Sierra Nevada mountain range was named in his honour in 1895.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1928, a house at Richard Hale School (then called Hertford Grammar School, where he had been a pupil) was named after Wallace.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The Alfred Russel Wallace building is a prominent feature of the Glyntaff campus at the University of South Wales, by Pontypridd, with several teaching spaces and laboratories for science courses.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The Natural Sciences Building at Swansea University and lecture theatre at Cardiff University are named after him, as are impact craters on Mars and the Moon.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1986, the Royal Entomological Society mounted a year-long expedition to the Dumoga-Bone National Park in North Sulawesi named Project Wallace.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] A group of Indonesian islands is known as the Wallacea biogeographical region in his honour, and Operation Wallacea, named after the region, awards "Alfred Russel Wallace Grants" to undergraduate ecology students.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Several hundred species of plants and animals, both living and fossil, have been named after Wallace, such as the gecko *Cyrtodactylus wallacei*, and the freshwater stingray *Potamotrygon wallacei*.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] More recently, several new species have been named during the bicentenary year of Wallace's birth, including a large spider from Peru, *Linothele wallacei* Sherwood *et al*., 2023 and a South African weevil, *Nama wallacei* Meregalli & Borovec, 2023.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 2002, historian of science Michael Shermer published a quantitative analysis of Wallace's publications.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He found that Wallace had published 22 full-length books and at least 747 shorter pieces, 508 of which were scientific papers (191 of them published in *Nature*).
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He further broke down the 747 short pieces by their primary subjects: 29% were on biogeography and natural history, 27% were on evolutionary theory, 25% were social commentary, 12% were on anthropology, and 7% were on spiritualism and phrenology.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] An online bibliography of Wallace's writings has more than 750 entries.
[src:acclimatisation-society/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The standard author abbreviation Wallace is used to indicate this person as the author when citing a botanical name.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] The **American Acclimatization Society** was a group founded in New York City in 1871 dedicated to introducing European flora and fauna into North America for both economic and cultural reasons.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] The group inspired the formation of similar groups around the world, particularly in countries that had been colonized by Europeans.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] Even before the American society's founding, wealthy New York residents and naturalists had deliberately sought to introduce foreign animals.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] In 1864 the commissioners of Central Park had introduced Java sparrows, house sparrows, chaffinches and blackbirds into the park.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] The European sparrows were reported to have "multiplied amazingly".
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] They quickly became one of the most common birds in New York, though the others did not seem to do as well.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] After the society's founding, such efforts were redoubled.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] The group's annual meeting held at the Great New York Aquarium in 1877 reported that the release of 50 pairs of English skylarks into Central Park had only been a partial success, since most had flown across the East River to take up residence at Newtown and Canarsie in Brooklyn.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] At the meeting, the recent release of European starlings, Japanese finches and pheasants into the park were noted.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] The meeting adjourned with the group resolved to introduce more chaffinches, skylarks, European robins and tits—"birds which were useful to the farmer and contributed to the beauty of the groves and fields"—in the city.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] By 1877, New York pharmacist Eugene Schieffelin was the chairman of the society.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] Another notable member of the society was wealthy silk merchant Alfred Edwards, who constructed bird boxes around Manhattan to help house sparrows to breed.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] Some accounts of Schieffelin's efforts claim that he had resolved that, as an aesthetic goal, the organization should introduce every bird species mentioned in the works of William Shakespeare.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] However, multiple historians have disputed this claim, as no contemporary source corroborates this claim of a link to Shakespeare.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] The American poet William Cullen Bryant admired Schieffelin's efforts and wrote his poem *The Olde-World Sparrow* ("A winged settler has taken his place/With Teutons and Men of the Celtic race") after spending an evening with Schieffelin, who had just released a shipment of sparrows into his yard.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] Starlings had been introduced in the United States by the mid-1870s.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] The American Acclimatization Society added another 100 starlings to the total in 1890 and 1891.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] By the early 21st century, more than 200 million European starlings had spread throughout the United States, Mexico and Canada.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] Their aggressive competition for nesting cavities has long been thought to be responsible for the collapse of some native bird populations, among them New York's state bird, the eastern bluebird, though some research has found that this is unlikely, except in the case of sapsuckers.
[src:acclimatisation-society/american-acclimatization-society] For its role in the decline of local native species and the damages to agriculture, the European starling has been included in the IUCN List of the world's 100 worst invasive species.
